# React Syntax Best Practices

## Core React Syntax Rules

### Component Structure

- Use functional components with hooks (no class components)
- Use TypeScript for all component props and state
- Prefer `const` for component declarations
- Use proper prop destructuring with default values

### JSX Best Practices

- Use semantic HTML elements (`<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<nav>`)
- Always include `key` prop for mapped elements
- Use proper boolean attributes (`disabled={true}` not `disabled="true"`)
- Escape special characters in JSX (`&apos;`, `&quot;`, `&amp;`)
- Use proper event handler naming (`onClick`, `onSubmit`, `onChange`)

### State Management

- Use `useState` for local component state
- Use `useCallback` for functions passed as props or in dependency arrays
- Use `useMemo` for expensive calculations
- Use `useRef` for DOM references and stable values
- Use `useEffect` with proper dependency arrays

### Event Handling

- Use arrow functions for inline handlers: `onClick={() => handleClick()}`
- Use `useCallback` for reusable handlers
- Prevent default behavior when needed: `onSubmit={(e) => { e.preventDefault(); }}`
- Use proper event types: `onChange={(e: ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {}}`

### Conditional Rendering

- Use ternary operators for simple conditions: `{isLoading ? <Spinner /> : <Content />}`
- Use logical AND for conditional elements: `{isVisible && <Modal />}`
- Use early returns for complex conditions
- Avoid nested ternaries - use separate variables or components

### List Rendering

- Always include unique `key` prop: `{items.map(item => <Item key={item.id} />)}`
- Use stable keys (IDs, not array indices)
- Extract list items to separate components for complex items
- Use proper array methods: `map`, `filter`, `reduce`

### Props and Children

- Use proper prop types with TypeScript interfaces
- Use default props with destructuring: `const Component = ({ title = 'Default' }) => {}`
- Use children prop for composition: `{children}`
- Use spread operator sparingly and intentionally

### Performance Optimizations

- Use `React.memo` for expensive components
- Use `useCallback` for event handlers passed to child components
- Use `useMemo` for expensive calculations
- Avoid creating objects/arrays in render

### Error Handling

- Use error boundaries for component error catching
- Use proper error states in components
- Handle loading states appropriately
- Use try-catch in async operations

### Accessibility

- Use proper ARIA attributes
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Include proper alt text for images
- Use proper form labels and associations
- Ensure keyboard navigation works

### Code Style

- Use consistent indentation (2 spaces)
- Use proper component naming (PascalCase)
- Use proper file naming (kebab-case for files, PascalCase for components)
- Use proper import/export syntax
- Use proper TypeScript types

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- Don't use `any` type - use proper TypeScript types
- Don't use array indices as keys
- Don't create functions in render
- Don't use inline styles for complex styling
- Don't use `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` unless absolutely necessary
- Don't use `console.log` in production code
- Don't use `var` - use `const` and `let`
- Don't use class components
- Don't use `componentWillMount` or other deprecated lifecycle methods
